      {
        "paragraph_index": 2,
        "text": "### Chemistry Insight\n- The **first pKa of −1.2** is remarkably low (even negative!), meaning H₂C₂O₄ is a *strong* acid for its first proton — comparable in strength to HCl. This is due to the strong electron-withdrawing effect of the adjacent carbonyl group stabilizing the HL⁻ anion.\n- The **second pKa of 3.8** is more typical of a weak carboxylic acid. The second proton is harder to remove because the already-negatively-charged HL⁻ resists further deprotonation.\n- The large gap (~5 pKa units) between the two steps means that at physiological pH (~7.4), oxalate exists almost entirely as the fully deprotonated **oxalate dianion (L²⁻)** — the form responsible for kidney stone formation when it precipitates with Ca²⁺.\n\n*Source: NIST SRD-46 (ligand_8872, metal_68/H⁺, 25 °C, I = 0.1 M)*",
